The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Chennai, June 4: Eleven persons were killed when a state transport bus fell into a 200ft-deep gorge in Tamil Nadus Nilgiris district today. Fifty-three people were injured.          
	The accident occurred when the over-crowded bus from Ooty to Bokkapuram was negotiating a hairpin bend at Bison Point, 20km from Ooty, and swerved to the left to let a car from the opposite side pass on a narrow road, police sources said. The victims included its driver and conductor, and a child. Some of the injured are in serious condition.                   
	Melbourne, (PTI): The Australian defence chief will apologise to Bollywood actress Tania Zaetta for the false claim that she had sex with the countrys soldiers deployed in Afghanistan. Air Chief Marshal Angus Houston said there was no evidence for the allegation, an Australian Associated Press report said on Wednesday.                   
	Panaji (PTI): Goa police said on Wednesday that the charges of British teenager Scarlett Keeling being raped before her death were established on circumstantial evidence though the medical report ruled out rape. Scarletts bruised semi-nude body was found on Anjuna beach on February 18.                   
	Srinagar (PTI): The Jammu and Kashmir human rights commission on Wednesday recommended a compensation of Rs 2 lakh each for the relatives of three persons allegedly tortured to death by army personnel in January 2000.                   
	Amritsar (PTI): Punjab police have arrested two persons, including a Bangladeshi, for crossing over to Pakistan through the Attari checkpost. He was handed over by the Pakistan rangers who alleged that Abu Tahir was smuggled out with the help of an Indian truck driver, Harbhajan Singh, who has also been arrested.                  
	 Srinagar (PTI): Bemina Bridge, said to be the longest bridge in Kashmir, will be opened to public next week, officials have said. Work on the 250m long bridge, which cost nearly Rs 10 crore, was started in 1988.                                                                                                                         
